# adder/compiler/ssa_llvm.ad
#
# OPTIONAL "release/fast" LLVM backend for the self-hosted Adder compiler (a
# SPIKE, not the default). It walks the Phase-1 SSA IR (ssa.ad) — the value/
# instruction model documented there as "the LLVM subset" — and emits TEXTUAL
# LLVM IR (.ll) for every function the SSA path accepts. The .ll is then handed
# to clang-19 / llc (no libLLVM linkage), which runs LLVM's optimizer and code
# generator, exactly like Rust's MIR->LLVM lowering.
#
# ISOLATION
# ---------
# codegen.ad (the seed backend) is UNCHANGED and stays the DEFAULT + the self-
# hosting bootstrap. ssa.ad is UNCHANGED — this module only READS its arenas
# (sv_*, sb_*, arg_*) after ssa_build_function() populates them, and CALLS the
# codegen global/enum/class layout helpers to populate the globals table so the
# SSA array/scalar-global paths resolve. It never emits machine code and never
# mutates the AST, so with this module unreferenced the default path is byte-
# identical. It is reached only through the dedicated --emit-llvm driver lane
# (tests/fuzz/ssa_llvm_dump_driver.ad).
#
# VALUE MODEL / TYPING
# --------------------
# LLVM is strongly typed; the SSA IR is mostly i64 with i1 for compares/bools and
# integer-modelled addresses. Canonical rule: every emitted %vN register is i64
# EXCEPT SVO_ICMP results and explicitly-i1 (SVT_I1) values, which are i1.
#   * SVO_CONST / SVO_UNDEF: no instruction — inlined as a literal / `undef`.
#   * SVO_LOAD of a sub-word width: `load iW` then zext/sext to i64 -> %vN is i64.
#   * SVO_STORE of a sub-word width: `trunc i64 -> iW` then `store iW`.
#   * SVO_TRUNC (narrowing cast / narrow-local write): `trunc i64 -> iW` then
#     zext/sext back to i64 (models the legacy sized-store + extended-load).
#   * Addresses (SVO_GLOBALADDR + base+idx*scale arithmetic) are i64; LOAD/STORE
#     `inttoptr` them to iW* at the point of access — a pure byte-addressed model
#     that matches the SSA's integer address arithmetic exactly.
#   * SVO_CONDBR coerces a non-i1 condition with `icmp ne i64 cond, 0`.
# Globals become opaque `[BYTES x i8]` symbols; a GLOBALADDR is `ptrtoint` of the
# symbol, recovered from (byte-offset, is_bss) via a reverse scan of the globals
# table (the SSA erased the symbol into an offset).

